Exercises

Exercise 1

1846 rows, 3 columns; 3 variables: dataset, x, and y.

Exercise 2

Plotting the data in the dino dataset:

dino_data <- datasaurus_dozen %>%
  filter(dataset == "dino")

ggplot(data = dino_data, mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point()

Calculating the correlation between x and y in this dataset:

dino_data %>%
  summarize(r = cor(x, y))
## # A tibble: 1  1
##         r
##     <dbl>
## 1 -0.0645

From viewing the data visualization, we see that it wouldnt make sense to calculate a correlation between x and y in this data set since there is not a linear relationship. However, if we do calculate a correlation, we get r = -0.0645.

Exercise 3

Plotting the data in the star dataset:

star_data <- datasaurus_dozen %>%
    filter(dataset == "star")

ggplot(data = star_data, mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
    geom_point()

Calculating the correlation between x and y in this dataset:

star_data %>%
    summarize(r = cor(x, y))
## # A tibble: 1  1
##         r
##     <dbl>
## 1 -0.0630

Although the star data looks very different from the dino data, x and y have almost the same correlation.

Exercise 4

Plotting the data in the circle dataset:

Again, this data set has a correlation very similar to the previous data sets.

Exercise 5

Plotting all datasets at once:

ggplot(datasaurus_dozen, aes(x = x, y = y, color = dataset)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~dataset, ncol = 3) +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

Generating all summary correlation coefficients:

datasaurus_dozen %>%
  group_by(dataset) %>%
